00:32:08.930 --> 00:32:11.300 align:middle line:84%
is I'm drawing the
fiber out so it's not

00:32:11.300 --> 00:32:13.210 align:middle line:90%
too thick and not too thin.

00:32:13.210 --> 00:32:17.507 align:middle line:90%


00:32:17.507 --> 00:32:19.090 align:middle line:84%
The way it's different
from sheep wool

00:32:19.090 --> 00:32:20.710 align:middle line:90%
is it doesn't have lanolin.

00:32:20.710 --> 00:32:22.030 align:middle line:90%
There's no smell.

00:32:22.030 --> 00:32:23.980 align:middle line:90%
Sheep wool has an odor to it.

00:32:23.980 --> 00:32:24.970 align:middle line:90%
That's the lanolin.

00:32:24.970 --> 00:32:27.850 align:middle line:84%
And the lanolin is greasy,
and it collects dirt.

00:32:27.850 --> 00:32:29.440 align:middle line:84%
So that if you were
a sheep farmer,

00:32:29.440 --> 00:32:31.420 align:middle line:84%
and you were going
to share your sheep,

00:32:31.420 --> 00:32:37.510 align:middle line:84%
you have to scour the lanolin
in acids to remove it.

00:32:37.510 --> 00:32:39.678 align:middle line:84%
And that's putting a
chemical on the fiber

00:32:39.678 --> 00:32:41.470 align:middle line:84%
and into your environment
that you wouldn't

00:32:41.470 --> 00:32:45.250 align:middle line:90%
need to have if you had alpaca.

00:32:45.250 --> 00:32:46.690 align:middle line:90%
Well, she's weaving.

00:32:46.690 --> 00:32:49.030 align:middle line:84%
This is one of the
simplest kinds of looms.

00:32:49.030 --> 00:32:51.490 align:middle line:84%
It's called the
rigid heddle loom.

00:32:51.490 --> 00:32:54.072 align:middle line:84%
How long ago did you
start weaving, Kirsten?

00:32:54.072 --> 00:32:55.270 align:middle line:90%
>> About 5 minutes.

